// Reject fixture: out_of_scope_type_param_receive_fn — a type-parameter name is
// in scope only for the item that declares it. `id` declares `<T>`, so `T` is
// valid inside `id`. The actor's `receive fn bad` declares no type params, so
// its `x: T` names a type that is out of scope. The checker must report it at
// the annotation with `unknown type `T``, rather than exempt it merely because
// `id` declares a `T` somewhere program-wide and leak an opaque `Ty::named` —
// here the leak previously aborted as `E_MIR: unknown type` at the MIR
// boundary instead of failing closed at the annotation.
//
// Companion to out_of_scope_type_param (free fn): proves the scope-aware
// exemption holds on the actor receive-fn signature path.
//
// Harness verb: hew check
// Expected: rejected with `unknown type `T`` at `bad`'s parameter annotation.
fn id<T>(x: T) -> T { x }

actor Worker {
    receive fn bad(x: T) {}
}

fn main() -> i64 { 0 }
